do we need to metion anywhere aws access key and secret key or ecr username and password for buildspec ci/cd?

 No! You don't need to mention AWS keys anywhere.

Why no keys needed:

CodeBuild runs with IAM Role
        │
        ▼
IAM Role has permissions
        │
        ▼
AWS CLI and boto3 automatically
use the role credentials
        │
        ▼
No access key needed ✅
No secret key needed ✅

-----------------------------------------------
How authentication works:

CodeBuild starts
        │
        ▼
AWS attaches IAM role automatically
(codebuild-aws-pipeline-build-service-role)
        │
        ▼
All AWS CLI commands use role:
├── aws ecr get-login-password  → uses role ✅
├── aws eks update-kubeconfig   → uses role ✅
├── aws s3 cp                   → uses role ✅
└── aws secretsmanager get      → uses role ✅

No keys needed anywhere ✅
--------------------------------------------------
What IAM role needs:

CodeBuild role must have these policies:
├── AmazonECR FullAccess          → ECR login/push
├── AmazonEKSClusterPolicy        → EKS access
├── SecretsManagerReadWrite       → read secrets
└── CloudWatchLogsFullAccess      → write logs

You already added these in Step 7 ✅
--------------------------------------
Summary:

AWS Access Key  → NOT needed ❌
AWS Secret Key  → NOT needed ❌
ECR Username    → NOT needed ❌
ECR Password    → NOT needed ❌

Everything uses:
→ CodeBuild IAM Role ✅
→ Automatic authentication ✅
→ No credentials in code ✅
→ No credentials in secrets ✅

This is the beauty of IAM roles!
---------------------------------------------------------------
GitHub Actions has its own built-in secrets management.

GitHub Repo → Settings → Secrets and Variables → Actions → New Secret

In GitHub Actions we store sensitive values like passwords and tokens in GitHub Secrets and access them using ${{ secrets.NAME }} — they are masked in logs. 
Non-sensitive config values go in GitHub Variables accessed via ${{ vars.NAME }}. ✅

------------------------------------------
For Jenkins, we use Jenkins Credentials to manage secrets.

Where to add:

Jenkins UI → Manage Jenkins → Credentials → Global → Add Credentials

Each CI/CD tool has its own secrets store. 
GitHub Secrets = GitHub Actions only. 
Jenkins Credentials = Jenkins only. They are completely separate. ✅
